A"},"death":{"year":2001,"month":4,"day":2,"city":"Front Royal","county":"Warren County","state":"Virginia","age":61,"cause":"cancer (non-Hodgkin lymphoma); died at Rock Hill Farm"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Raymond Richard Guest Jr.","first_name":"Raymond","last_name":"Guest","middle_name":"Richard","married_names":[],"suffix":"Jr.","nickname":"Andy","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1779680903/andyguest_zsjcgs.png"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[{"branch":"United States Marine Corps Reserves","service_years":"circa 1962-1963","note":"Took year off from Yale to serve in Marine Corps Reserves between Yale Class of 1963 and Class of 1964 (graduated with latter). Cold War era; no specific war. Proudly sported Marine Corps tattoo on upper arm."}],"burial":{"place":"Old Chapel Cemetery","city":"Millwood","county":"Clarke County","state":"Virginia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Virginia House of Delegates 1972-2000; minority leader","body":"Andy Guest served seven terms (28 years, 1972-2000) in the Virginia House of Delegates as a Republican from Warren County. He served as House Minority Leader from December 1985 to November 1991 — a pioneering Republican in an era when his party held few seats in Richmond. He championed pari-mutuel betting (his 1988 bill led to the Colonial Downs racetrack) and land-and-wildlife conservation throughout his tenure."},{"number":2,"category":"achievement","header":"State park named for him while still living","body":"In 1995 the Commonwealth of Virginia named a state park in his honor: the Shenandoah River Raymond R. 'Andy' Guest Jr. State Park, on the south fork of the Shenandoah River in Warren County near his Rock Hill Farm home. His Yale '64 classmate Chris Getman noted that Andy was 'the only person in history to have a national park named after him while still living.' He and his wife Mary Scott put easements on Rock Hill Farm and bequeathed its 3.5 miles of riverfront to the state."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Voted from hospital chemo isolation, 1994 session","body":"Diagnosed with non-Hodgkin lymphoma in 1996 and given six months to live, Guest underwent a stem-cell transplant he believed extended his life by five years. During earlier 1994 chemo isolation he missed 35 days of the General Assembly session but the legislature set up a system to enable him to witness floor proceedings and to vote remotely from his hospital bed — a striking testament to his bipartisan respect. He sponsored four bills and budget amendments from isolation that session."}],"slug":"raymond-guest-jr-1939"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}